blocks.name: numthcor
blocks.content: Any set is strictly dominated by some ordinal. (Contributed by NM, 22-Oct-2003.)
blocks.origin:
thm numthcor(setvar s0, class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wcel(c0, c1), wrex(s0, con0, wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0))))
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
} = {
  vtoclg(hs0, c0, c1, wrex(s0, con0, wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0))), wrex(s0, con0, wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0))))
  rexbidv(s0, con0, wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0)))
  breq1(cv(hs0), c0, csdm, cv(s0))
  ax-mp(wrex(s0, con0, wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0))), wrex(s0, con0, wbr(cv(s0), cen, cpw(cv(hs0)))))
  numth2(s0, cpw(cv(hs0)))
  vpwex(hs0)
  reximi(s0, con0, wbr(cv(s0), cen, cpw(cv(hs0))), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)))
  sylancr(wbr(cv(s0), cen, cpw(cv(hs0))), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0))), wbr(cpw(cv(hs0)), cen, cv(s0)))
  canth2(cv(hs0))
  vex(hs0)
  ensym(cv(s0), cpw(cv(hs0)))
  sdomentr(cv(hs0), cpw(cv(hs0)), cv(s0))
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.w(wrex(s0, con0, wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0))))
  diff.wceq.s(s0, cv(hs0), c0)
  diff.cpw.s(s0, cv(hs0))
  diff.cv.s(s0, hs0)
  diffss.ex(s0, hs0)
  diff.hs0.s(s0)
}

thm numthcor(setvar s0, class c0, class c1) {
  ⊢ (c0 ∈ c1 → ∃(s0 ∈ On, c0[≺]s0))

} = {
  vtoclg(hs0, c0, c1, ∃(s0 ∈ On, c0[≺]s0), ∃(s0 ∈ On, hs0[≺]s0))

  sylancr(s0[≅]P(hs0), hs0[≺]s0, hs0[≺]P(hs0), P(hs0)[≅]s0)
  canth2(hs0)
  vex(hs0)

  sdomentr(hs0, P(hs0), s0)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)

blocks.name: weth
blocks.content: Well-ordering theorem: any set ` A ` can be well-ordered. This is an equivalent of the Axiom of Choice. Theorem 6 of [Suppes] p. 242. First proved by Ernst Zermelo (the "Z" in ZFC) in 1904. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 5-Jan-2013.)
blocks.origin:
thm weth(setvar s0, class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wcel(c0, c1), wex(s0, wwe(cv(s0), c0)))
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
} = {
  vtoclg(hs0, c0, c1, wex(s0, wwe(cv(s0), c0)), wex(s0, wwe(cv(s0), cv(hs0))))
  exbidv(s0, wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wwe(cv(s0), cv(hs0)), wwe(cv(s0), c0))
  weeq2(cv(hs0), c0, cv(s0))
  axaci(hs0, wex(s0, wwe(cv(s0), cv(hs0))))
  dfac8(hs0, s0)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.w(wex(s0, wwe(cv(s0), c0)))
  diff.wceq.s(s0, cv(hs0), c0)
  diff.cv.s(s0, hs0)
  diffss.ex(s0, hs0)
  diff.hs0.s(s0)
}

thm weth(setvar s0, class c0, class c1) {

  ⊣ d(s0, c0)
} = {
  vtoclg(hs0, c0, c1, ∃(s0, s0 ≤ c0), ∃(s0, s0 ≤ hs0))
  exbidv(s0, hs0 = c0, s0 ≤ hs0, s0 ≤ c0)
  weeq2(hs0, c0, s0)
  axaci(hs0, ∃(s0, s0 ≤ hs0))
  dfac8(hs0, s0)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.w(∃(s0, s0 ≤ c0))
  diff.wceq.s(s0, hs0, c0)
  diff.cv.s(s0, hs0)
  diffss.ex(s0, hs0)
  diff.hs0.s(s0)
}

blocks.name: zorn2g
blocks.content: Zorn's Lemma of [Monk1] p. 117. This version of ~ zorn2 avoids the Axiom of Choice by assuming that ` A ` is well-orderable. (Contributed by NM, 6-Apr-1997.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 9-May-2015.)

  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)

blocks.name: zorng
blocks.content: Zorn's Lemma. If the union of every chain (with respect to inclusion) in a set belongs to the set, then the set contains a maximal element. Theorem 6M of [Enderton] p. 151. This version of ~ zorn avoids the Axiom of Choice by assuming that ` A ` is well-orderable. (Contributed by NM, 12-Aug-2004.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 9-May-2015.)

blocks.name: zorn2
blocks.content: Zorn's Lemma of [Monk1] p. 117. This theorem is equivalent to the Axiom of Choice and states that every partially ordered set ` A ` (with an ordering relation ` R ` ) in which every totally ordered subset has an upper bound, contains at least one maximal element. The main proof consists of lemmas ~ zorn2lem1 through ~ zorn2lem7 ; this final piece mainly changes bound variables to eliminate the hypotheses of ~ zorn2lem7 . (Contributed by NM, 6-Apr-1997.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 9-May-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm zorn2(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wa(wpo(c0, c1), wal(s0, wi(wa(wss(cv(s0), c1), wor(c0, cv(s0))), wrex(s1, c1, wral(s2, cv(s0), wo(wbr(cv(s2), c0, cv(s1)), wceq(cv(s2), cv(s1)))))))), wrex(s1, c1, wral(s3, c1, wn(wbr(cv(s1), c0, cv(s3))))))
  -| wcel(c1, universe)
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s3)
  -| diffss(s2, s3)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s2, c0)
  -| diffsc(s2, c1)
  -| diffsc(s3, c0)
  -| diffsc(s3, c1)
} = {
  mp3an1(wpo(c0, c1), wal(s0, wi(wa(wss(cv(s0), c1), wor(c0, cv(s0))), wrex(s1, c1, wral(s2, cv(s0), wo(wbr(cv(s2), c0, cv(s1)), wceq(cv(s2), cv(s1))))))), wrex(s1, c1, wral(s3, c1, wn(wbr(cv(s1), c0, cv(s3))))), wcel(c1, cdm(ccrd)))
  ax-mp(wcel(c1, cdm(ccrd)), wcel(c1, universe))
  numth3(c1, universe)
  zorn2g(s0, s1, s2, s3, c1, c0)
}

blocks.name: zorn
blocks.content: Zorn's Lemma. If the union of every chain (with respect to inclusion) in a set belongs to the set, then the set contains a maximal element. This theorem is equivalent to the Axiom of Choice. Theorem 6M of [Enderton] p. 151. See ~ zorn2 for a version with general partial orderings. (Contributed by NM, 12-Aug-2004.)
blocks.origin:
thm zorn(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, class c0) {
  |- wi(wal(s0, wi(wa(wss(cv(s0), c0), wor(crpss, cv(s0))), wcel(cuni(cv(s0)), c0))), wrex(s1, c0, wral(s2, c0, wn(wpss(cv(s1), cv(s2))))))
  -| wcel(c0, universe)
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s2, c0)
} = {
  mpan(wal(s0, wi(wa(wss(cv(s0), c0), wor(crpss, cv(s0))), wcel(cuni(cv(s0)), c0))), wrex(s1, c0, wral(s2, c0, wn(wpss(cv(s1), cv(s2))))), wcel(c0, cdm(ccrd)))
  ax-mp(wcel(c0, cdm(ccrd)), wcel(c0, universe))
  numth3(c0, universe)
  zorng(s0, s1, s2, c0)
}

  ⊢ (∀(s0,((s0 ⊆ c0 ∧ ⊊ ≺ s0)→ ⋃ s0 ∈ c0))→ ∃(s1 ∈ c0, ∀(s2 ∈ c0, ¬ s1 ⊊ s2)))

blocks.name: ttukey2g
blocks.content: The Teichmüller-Tukey Lemma ~ ttukey with a slightly stronger conclusion: we can set up the maximal element of ` A ` so that it also contains some given ` B e. A ` as a subset. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)

blocks.name: ttukey
blocks.content: The Teichmüller-Tukey Lemma, an Axiom of Choice equivalent. If ` A ` is a nonempty collection of finite character, then ` A ` has a maximal element with respect to inclusion. Here "finite character" means that ` x e. A ` iff every finite subset of ` x ` is in ` A ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)

blocks.name: axdc
blocks.content: This theorem derives ~ ax-dc using ~ ax-ac and ~ ax-inf . Thus, _AC_ implies _DC_, but not vice-versa (so that ZFC is strictly stronger than ZF+DC). (New usage is discouraged.) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 25-Jan-2013.)

  brdom4(hs0, s1, s2, c0, c1)
